vekWy7Cd5C9SmeA7KTqiOLHkbL3cMI67hUYBVwxI4Bh86A6m1_xcLuPEaLGl-YjxSRBL3Uut3kx=
018tooJls3HttyE9KSnlC1VatPaXME4b42LJsEbzPW4p_kekoVwN3sIHgtd6hqI14IJzoXoWScF=
G6igHYd5tiPnoKybpaFZhO3n_epuiq1PQctuSgX7fWaRrL9SWZpzNurL-fbUjHWPvh4TRjAB3UW=
kXlz_GE1PjJgbbzdB1bxXTI39ox_aFReBhkz1TI6Kj6QlutSmov5_-xc1z5Ef] arguing that=
 the libertarian idea of freedom is incomplete. Libertarians of the Robert =
Nozick variety tend to conceive of society as having only two levels =E2=80=
=94 government, and individuals. In this conception, freedoms can only be t=
aken away by the government. But I argued that there are key mezzanine inst=
itutions =E2=80=94 corporations, churches, universities, schools, and so on=
 =E2=80=94 that sit somewhere between government and the individual, and ho=
ld real power over individuals, and that this power shouldn=E2=80=99t be ig=
nored when we think about what makes for a free society. If mezzanine insti=
tutions oppress individuals, that=E2=80=99s real systematic oppression, and=
 a real loss of human freedom, even if the government stands back and washe=
s its hands of the whole situation.
I doubt I managed to convince many libertarians. But today, I see some prog=
ressives arguing for the old libertarian idea that if the government isn=E2=
=80=99t throwing you in jail, your freedoms haven=E2=80=99t been abridged. =
Conservatives=E2=80=99 complaints that their =E2=80=9Cfree speech=E2=80=9D =
is being stifled by social media platforms are often met with an invocation=
 of the famous XKCD comic [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkN2OhCAMhZ9=
muDT8Kl5wsTf7GgShjuwqGKgz49svrknTNmna0-94h_DM5TR7rkiuZPHcwSR41xUQoZCjQrExGK=
6p4EKSYGRgWmkSq50LwObiarAcQPZjWqN3GHO6FoQSUpHFDBMH4Wch-iDpoEepHQzzyIIKnAJ1t=
