mLrC1_3zfqmHpNuTd_WYKjr_e10ixfzkurTJVbpYLwTbBtuRIp4WkptWCDcd3h7989onJCjNu2A=
dGtZLKsd-6HX74qZp-LKnYpRsJE0x5LaVTMpu2WNq_vwBc3R9MA] where a stick figure r=
eminds us that =E2=80=9CThe 1st Amendment doesn=E2=80=99t shield you from c=
riticism or consequences.=E2=80=9D
And of course that=E2=80=99s perfectly correct. The 1st Amendment doesn=E2=
=80=99t shield you from social consequences. But is the kind of speech prot=
ection offered by the 1st Amendment the only protection that we could ever =
want or need? If the entire world stood ready to fire you, ostracize you, a=
nd leave you friendless and impoverished for saying you liked kittens, woul=
d you really be free?=20
I don=E2=80=99t think so. Freedom, really, is what makes people feel free, =
and a world that turns you into an unemployable pariah for saying you liked=
 kittens wouldn=E2=80=99t feel very free at all. What the legal implication=
s of that realization should be, I don=E2=80=99t quite know, but I think it=
=E2=80=99s important that we recognize the power of non-governmental instit=
utions and the value of freedom from oppression by those institutions.
Anyway, here=E2=80=99s my original post from 2011:
I have not been surprised by any of the quotes that have recently come to l=
ight from=C2=A0Ron Paul's racist newsletters [https://email.mg2.substack.co=
m/c/eJxFkEtuxCAMhk8zLCOemWTBopteAzngTGgJREAmze1LmkUlywb58dufhYqvlE-9pVLJ5Uw=
9N9QRjxKwVsxkL5iNd5oPVHAhidPSsUENxBczZ8QVfNA170i2fQreQvUpXg1CCanIooFPlPUAkq=
